{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_lily_ver01/data/sn78002169/00279558868/1945090701/0074.xml":{"full_text":"Truman Submits Plans\nI\n(Continued from Page One)\nTo reach those ends, Mr. Tru\nman said, eight policies will be\npursued quick demobilization of\narmed forces no longer needed;\ncancellation and settlement of war\ncontracts speedily; clearance of\nwar plants; a holding of the line\non prices and rents until fair com\npetition becomes operable; holding\nwages in line where increases\nwould bring inflationary price\nrises, but restoring collective bar\ngaining where price ceilings would\nnot be endangered; removing all\nwartime controls wherever pos\nsible, but keeping those necessary\nto reconversion and those tending\ntoward inflation, and finally, pre\nventing rapid decrease of wage in\ntomes or purchasing power.\n\u201cThe major objective, of course,\n0 to reestablish an expanded\npeacetime industry, trade and\nagriculture, and to do it as quickly\nas possible.\u2019\u2019 he said.\nHe warned that speed was of\nthe essence in transforming war\nplans and war workers into peace\ntime pursuits, and in making pro\nvision for the returning fighter and\nreplacing him with new draftees\nand volunteers. Haste likewise is\nthe order of the day, he said, in\ngaining full employment and in\nproviding compensation for the\nworker temporarily unemployed.\nBut, the Chief Executive empha\nsized, there are portions of this\nprogram where caution and re\nstraint will serve the better part\nof reconversion. Some wartime\ncontrols must be retained. Selec\ntive service should be continued\nso that fresh blood can replace\nwar weary veterans. Some foods\nmust remain on the rationed list\nfor some time, and the War Pro\nduction Board will have to support\nthe stabilization program so long\nas material shortages continue.\nManagement and labor must not\nreduce wages or permit industrial\nstrife, Congress must not attempt\na major reduction in taxes now,\nexcept so far as is necessary to\naid reconversion and expansion.\nSmall business and the man on\nHie farm must be given a lift by\nConeress.\n\u201cThe next few months are cru\ncial,\u201d Mr. Truman said. \u201cWhat we\ndo now will affect our American\nway of life for decades to come.\u201d\nTo re-emphasize the manifold\nproblems of reconversion and the\nneed for both speed and caution,\nhe appended to his message re\nports from Attorney General Tern\nC. Clark and Director of War Mo\nbilization and Reconversion John\nW. Snyder.\nClark delivered an opinion that\nthe broad basis of governmental\npower, on which many existing\nemergency and war time statutes\nrest, has not been terminated by\nthe unconditional surrender of Ger\nmany and Japan. The President\nwarned, in this connection, that\n\u201cthe time has not yet arrived for\nthe proclamation of the cessation\nof hostilities, much less the ter\nmination of the war.\u201d\n?n his report entitled \u201cThe Tran\nsition Phase One,\u201d Snyder out\n1 ned the work of reconversion to\ndate and listed the tasks ahead.\nReconversion is off to a good start,\nhe said, but some governmental\ncontrols will have to remain to\nguard against inflation and defla\ntion until the national economy is\nstabilized through full employment\nand full production.\nComprehensive as was his mes\nsage, Mr. Truman nevertheless\nmade plain that it is only the first\nof a series he will present in be\nhalf of national security. Others\nwill cover a universal training pro\ngram, unification of the armed\n\u2022ervices, and use and control of\natomic energy.\n\u201cI shall shortly communicate\nwith the Congress recommending\na national health program to pro\nvide adequate medical care for all\nAmericans and to protect them\nfrom financial loss and hardships\nresulting from illness and acci\ndent,\" he. said. \u201cI shall also com\nmunicate with the Congress with\nrespect to expanding our Social Se\ncurity system, and improving our\nprogram of education for our citi\nzens.\u201d\nThe President laid down 21 ma\njor factors in reconversion and\nmade recommendations, as fol\nlows:\n1. Unemployment Compensation.\nWar workers will be displaced\nduring reconversion. The govern\nment must help because this tran\nsition must be considered a war\ncost. Therefore the Congress must\nprovide aid to bring unemployment\ncompensation in ail states \u201cup to\nadequate standards\u2019\u2019 \u2014not less\nthan $25 a week lor 26 weeks in\none year.\n2. Fair Labor Standards Act.\nWar workers will suffer from\ndecreased income under early\npeacetime production. The 40 cent\nminimum wage now is inadequate.\nCongress should increase this stan\ndard to a level which will elimin\nate sub-standards of living. (Some\nCongressmen are recommending a\nminimum of 75 cents an hour.)\n\u201cI urge that the Congress act\npromptly,\u201d Mr. Truman said.\n\u201cThe wage structure on which\nbusiness men may make future\nplans should be settled quickly.\u201d\n3. Wartime Controls.\nThe government has held the\nline against inflation. Now the\nPrice Administrator must continue\nto resist pressure for higher pric\nes. Fats, oils and sugar will be\nscarce and must remain rationed.\nPrices must be held on both re\nconversion and cost-of-living items.\nControls will be released as expe\ndient. Agencies concerned are\nstudying the termination of war\ntime food subsidies, but some of!\nthe controls must be continued aft\ner the expiration of the second\nWar Powers Act on Dec. 31, 1945.\n\u201cI request the Congress, there\nfore, to extend the provisions of\nthe second War Powers Act, either\nin its present form or jvith appro\npriate limitations, preserving the\npowers necessary to achieve the\nobjectives I have outlined.\u201d\n4. War powers and Executive\nAgencies Reorganization.\nThe Attorney General has ruled\nthat the broad war time powers of\nthe executive did not terminate\nwith cessation of hostilities. If\neither +he President or Congress\nshould declare the w'ar terminated,\nwar agencies would expire within\nsix months, causing \u201cgreat confu\nsion and chaos in the government\u201d\n\u201cTherefore, I urge that the Con\ngress do not yet adopt a resolut on\nproclaiming the termination of the\nwar or the termination of the\nemergency or the cessation of hos\ntilities.\u201d\nWe must continue tjje program\nfor increased government efficien\ncy by permitting the President to I\nsubmit plans for reorganization of i\nthe executive department.\n5. Full Employment.\n\u201cGovernment must do its part1\nand assist industry and labor to\nget over the line from war to\npeace.\u201d Therefore it must gjve as\nsurances that facts on full em\nployment are made available. It\nmust assure stability as well as\nmaximum employment with prior\nity given to those efforts which\nmost highly stimulate normal em\nployment. Congress should speed\ni 1 y enact legislation embodying\n\"these vital assurances.\u201d\n6. Fair Employment Practice\nCommittee.\nWe must make every effort to\ncontinue fair employment prac\ntices during reconversion and aft\ner. The FEPC should be placed on\na permanent basis through legisla\ntion.\n7. Labor Dispute and Wage\nStabilization.\nThe national welfare requires\nfull production during reconver\nsion. To protect th s requirement,\nthe President will shortly call upon\na conference of labor and industry\n:o work out an agreement minimiz-1\nng labor disputes.\n\u201cThis is not the time for short\nsighted management to seize upon\nthe chance to reduce wages and\ntry to injure labor unions. Equally\nit is not the time for labor leaders\nto shirk their responsibility and\npermit widespread industrial\nstrife.\n8. United States Employment\nService Extension.\nPlacing war veterans and dis\nplaced war workers in jobs is a\nmajor reconversion problem. By\nlaw, the USES offices are to be\nreturned to state control within 90\ndays after hostilities cease. But\nany change now would impede re\nconversion, and \"I urgently recom\nmend that the Congress do not yet\nreturn the employment service to\nthe states.\u201d\n9. Agriculture.\nBecause of broad demands for\nfood here and abroad, the Agricul\nture Department is planning an\nother full production year. The\ngovernment must now aid the\nfarmers\u2019 reconversion. One way is\nto strengthen the machinery for\ncarrying out price support com\nmitments. Another way Congress\ncan aid is by a well-rounded crop\ninsurance program. A third is to\ncontinue and strengthen scientific\nresearch in agriculture and fores\ntry.\n10. Selective Service\nOur first concern is for the war\nveterans of several years service.\nBecause we have future defense\nand occupation commitments, w<\nshould release these men and pro\nvide replacements through contin\nuation of Selective Service and vol\nuntary enlistment. Congress should\nlegislate to remove restrictions\nfrom voluntary enlistments and tc\ncontinue Selective Service for the\ndrafting of men 18 to 26; Con\ngress should refrain from passing\na resolution to the effect that the\nwar is over, which would discharge\nall inductees' six months later.\n11. Housing\nThis presents the greatest single\nopportunity for post war private\ninvestment and employment. Ovei\nthe next 10 years, between 1,000,\n000 and 1,500,000 homes should be\nbuilt annually, representing an in\nvestment by private capital of be\ntween six and seven billion dollars\nyearly. Since this problem is high\non the list of matter for earlj\naction, \u201d1 urgently recommend\nthat Congress at an early date\nenact broad and comprehensive\nhousing legislation.\u201d\n12. Research\nProgress in scientific research\nand development is an indispens\nable cond tion to the future wel\nfare and security of the nation.\nDevelopment of the atomic bomb\nproved that. Congress early should\nadopt legislation to establish a\nsingle federal research agency\nwhose duties would be to promote\nand support research for national\ndefense and security, into the basic\nand social sciences, into medicine,\npublic health and allied fields;\nprovide financial assistance for\nyouths of ability, control and co\nordinate diverse federal scientific\nactivities, and make available the\nfruits of this federal research to\ncommerce, industry, agriculture\nand schools.\n13. Transition Tax Revision\nBecause taxes \u201cwill play a vital\nrole in attaining a prosperous\npeace,\u201d the enactment of a tran\nsitional tax bill to provide limited\nreductions for calendar 1946 is rec\n1 ommended. This should aim prin\ncipally at removing barriers to\nspeedy reconversion and to the ex\npansion of peacetime economy. A\nprogram will be ready shortly for\nCongress, which later should give\nconsideration to modernization ol\nthe federal tax structure.\n\u201cWe must reconcile ourselves tc\nthe fact that room for tax reduc\ntion at this time is limited,\u201d Mr,\nTruman said. \"A total war efforl\ncannot be liquidated overnight.\u201d\n14. Surplus-Property Disposal.\nDisposition of war plants anc\nequipment is of particular ur\ngency, and the appointment of\ni:\u2014: z _ =rr\nsingle administrator to replace the\nboard of three would eliminate\nmuch confusion, and Congress is\nurged to act on that matter now.\n15. Sma!i Business\nCongress\u2019 efforts to protect\nsmall business during the war paid\noff high dividends, and should be\ncontinued in peacetime.\n\u201cI am sure that Congress will\nsee to it that in its legislation ade\nquate protection and encourage\nment will be given to the small\nbusiness of the nation.\u201d\n16. Veterans\nAlthough many steps have been\ntaken to aid the veteran and his\ndependents, much more remains\nto be done by amendment and im\nprovement. Congress should give\nprompt attention to Veterans\u2019 Ad\nministration recommendations rel\native to hospital and medical care,\nvocational training, education, the\nloan features of the servicemen\u2019s\nreadjustment act, to insurance,\nand to increasing compensation for\nspecific injuries. Veterans should\nbe given assistance in getting their\nown farms, and should have Social\nSecurity coverage credit for their\nservice period.\nIT. Public Works and National I\nResources\nWe have been necessarily free\nduring the war years with out vast\nnatural resources, without consid\nering the future. Soil conservation\nwas forgotten, flood control pro\njects were suspended, land recla\nmation projects were ignored.\nNow we must recoup, both to re\nplenish our stores, and to provide\nmen and women with work Con\ngress should provide funds for\nthese works, to construct certain\nfederal buildings, improve roads\nexpand the inter-American high\nway, and to provide necessar\nports and airport facilities l a*\ntals and health certe-s ^\u00b0Spi'\ncourage states to cons \u2019ur en'\npublic works. Uct useful\n18. Lend-I.ease and p0,tWar\nReconstruction\nLend-lease is virtually over\nwhile its beneficiaries Vi r'd\nable to pay in dollars1\u00b0' be\nof its benefits, the oblioat!Lm\u00b0n\nnot cancelled, and settlement wn\nbe achieved. Now We ,u 1\nto economic cooperation in Pea^\n(Continued on page Six)\nGetting Up Nights\nHakes Manv Feel Old\nDo you suffer from Getting Up Nights,\nBacaache, Nervousness, Leg Pains, Dizai\nn's*. Swollen Ankles, Rheumatic Pains,\nBiadder Weakness, Painful Passages, or feel\nold and run-down, due to non-organic and\nnon-systemic Kidney and Bladder troubles?\nif so, here is good news: The very first dose\nof Cystex (a physician\u2019s prescription) usu\nally goes right to work helping the Kidneys\nflush out excess acids and wastes which may\n!\u2122'\u2019e caused your trouble. So take Cystex\nexactly as directed and watch for quick help\nand a rapid increase in pep, more youthful\nfeeling and joy in living. Cystex must sat\nisfy completely or money back is guaranteed\non return of empty package. Don't suffer\nanother day without trying Cyatex\u20143 Guar\nanteed sizes, 35c. 75c, $1.50 at druggista.\nfSSBjf LOOK! T